ting, raising children, racism and bigotry, and even the horrific lynching of two African American teenagers in 1935. The Colorado County residents' stories reveal an amazing resiliency and generosity of spirit, despite the hardships that have filled most of their lives. They also capture a rural way of life that was once common across the South, but is now gone forever.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aColorado County (Tex.). 0aOral historyzTexaszColorado County. 7aPhotography / Individual Photographers / General.2bisacsh1 aBoles, John B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoles, John.1 aPatten, Bob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPatten, Bob.40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/71305540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292759916423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292759916/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_AD  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_AD  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK